07573nam a22011655i 9780823290192DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780823290192  a(DE-B1597)577785  a(OCoLC)1235599361  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0420002bisacsh04a141.094322300aNothing Absolute :bGerman Idealism and the Question of Political Theology /ced. by Kirill Chepurin, Alex Dubilet. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives in Continental Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction Immanence, Genealogy, Delegitimation -- t1 Knot of the World German Idealism between Annihilation and Construction -- t2 Utopia and Political Theology in the “Oldest Systematic Program of German Idealism” -- t3 Relational Division -- t4 Otherwise Than Terror: Ten Theses on the Modernist Secular -- t5 Kant’s Unexpected Materialism: How the Object Saves Kant (and Us) from the Moral Law -- t6 Earth Unbounded: Division and Inseparability in Hölderlin and Günderrode -- t7 Kant with Sade with Hegel: The Death of God and the Joy of Reason -- t8 A Political Theology of Tolerance: Universalism and the Tragic Position of the Religious Minority -- t9 Hegel, Blackness, Sovereignty -- t10 Political Theology of the Death of God: Hegel and Derrida -- t11 Exception without Sovereignty: The Kenotic Eschatology of Schelling -- t12 Once More, from Below: The Concept of Reduplication and the Immanence of Political Theology -- t13 On the General Secular Contradiction: Secularization, Christianity, and Political Theology -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFeaturing scholars at the forefront of contemporary political theology and the study of German Idealism, Nothing Absolute explores the intersection of these two flourishing fields. Against traditional approaches that view German Idealism as a secularizing movement, this volume revisits it as the first fundamentally philosophical articulation of the political-theological problematic in the aftermath of the Enlightenment and the advent of secularity.Nothing Absolute reclaims German Idealism as a political-theological trajectory. Across the volume’s contributions, German thought from Kant to Marx emerges as crucial for the genealogy of political theology and for the ongoing reassessment of modernity and the secular. By investigating anew such concepts as immanence, utopia, sovereignty, theodicy, the Earth, and the world, as well as the concept of political theology itself, this volume not only rethinks German Idealism and its aftermath from a political-theological perspective but also demonstrates what can be done with (or against) German Idealism using the conceptual resources of political theology today.Contributors: Joseph Albernaz, Daniel Colucciello Barber, Agata Bielik-Robson, Kirill Chepurin, S. D. Chrostowska, Saitya Brata Das, Alex Dubilet, Vincent Lloyd, Thomas Lynch, James Martel, Steven Shakespeare, Oxana Timofeeva, Daniel Whistler  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aIdealism, German. 0aPolitical theologyzGermany. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Idealism.2bisacsh  aChristianity.  aGerman Idealism.  aPolitical Theology.  acritique.  aimmanence.  amodernity.  asecularism.  asecularity.  asovereignty.  atranscendence.1 aAlbernaz, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlbernaz, Joseph.1 aBarber, Daniel C.1 aBarber, Daniel Colucciello, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBielik-Robson, Agata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r